\'93Aeneas, why have you stepped forward,\uc0\u8232 standing here so far in front of all your men?\u8232 Does your heart prompt you to fight against me\u8232 in the hope you\'92ll win Priam\'92s royal honours\u8232 among horse-taming Trojans? If you kill me,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[180]\u8232 that won\'92t make Priam put his regal power\u8232 in your hands. For he has his own sons.\u8232 Besides, he\'92s healthy, and he is no fool.\u8232 Or have the Trojans given you some land\u8232 better than all the rest\'97a fine orchard,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0220\u8232 as well as land to plough\'97yours to keep,\u8232 if you kill me? You\'92ll find that hard to do.\u8232 My spear has sent you running once before.\u8232 Don\'92t you remember? You were alone.\u8232 I chased you away from your own cattle.\u8232 You scampered off, down Mount Ida\'92s slopes,\u8232 and quickly, too. That time we met, you ran\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[190]\u8232 and never once looked back, then hid yourself\u8232 inside Lyrnessus. But I destroyed that city\'97\u8232 I attacked it with help from Athena,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0230\u8232 as well as Father Zeus, seized their women\u8232 and took away their freedom. You were saved,\u8232 thanks to Zeus and other gods. But today,\u8232 I don\'92t think he\'92ll save you, as your heart hopes.\u8232 So I\'92m telling you to move back now,\u8232 retreat into the crowd. Don\'92t stand against me,\u8232 or you\'92ll come up against an evil time.\u8232 A man who doesn\'92t face the facts is stupid.\'94\
Aeneas then said in response:\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 \'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'93Son of Peleus,\uc0\u8232 don\'92t try to scare me off with words, as if\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0240\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[200]\u8232 I were a child. I, too, know well enough\u8232 how to hand out threats and insults. We both know\u8232 each other\'92s parents and our ancestry.\u8232 We\'92ve heard the famous tales of mortal men,\u8232 told long ago, though your eyes have not seen\u8232 my parents, nor mine yours. People say\u8232 you\'92re noble Peleus\'92 son, your mother\u8232 fair-haired Thetis, daughter of the sea.\u8232 Well, I claim I\'92m great Anchises\'92 son,\u8232 and Aphrodite is my mother. Today,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0250\u8232 one of them will mourn a dear dead son.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[210]\u8232 For I don\'92t think that you and I will leave\u8232 without a fight, once we\'92ve exchanged\u8232 some childish conversation. But if you wish,\u8232 then listen to me, so you\'92ll understand\u8232 my lineage well. Many people know it.\u8232 First cloud-gatherer Zeus fathered Dardanus,\u8232 who built Dardania, for sacred Ilion,\u8232 city of mortal men, was not yet built\u8232 here in the plain. His people settled there,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0260\u8232 by the slopes of Ida with its many springs.\u8232 Dardanus, in turn, was father to a son,\u8232 king Erichthonius, and he became\u8232 the richest of all mortals, possessing\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[220]\u8232 three thousand horses grazing in the fens,\u8232 all mares happy with their foals. Then North Wind\u8232 fell in love with them as they pastured there.\u8232 Taking on the form of a dark stallion,\u8232 he copulated with them. They conceived,\u8232 delivering twelve foals. When these foals played,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0270\u8232 running across the fertile farmland, they\'92d skim\u8232 the highest ears of corn and never break them,\u8232 or they\'92d race across the sea\'92s broad back,\u8232 gliding the surface of the breaking waves.\u8232 This Erichthonius had a son Tros,\u8232 who ruled the Trojans, and Tros then fathered\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[230]\u8232 three outstanding sons\'97Ilus, Assaracus,\u8232 and godlike Ganymede, the handsomest man\u8232 among all mortal men, so beautiful,\u8232 gods kidnapped him and made him cup bearer\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0280\u8232 to Zeus himself, so he\'92d live among immortals.\u8232 Ilus had a noble son, Laomedon,\u8232 who fathered Priam and Tithonus,\u8232 Clytius and warlike Hicataon.\u8232 Assaracus fathered his son Capys,\u8232 who had Anchises. He is my father.\u8232 Priam\'92s son is godlike Hector. That, then,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[240]\u8232 is my ancestry, the blood I boast of.\u8232 But as for courage, well, that\'92s up to Zeus,\u8232 who makes it less or greater as he wills,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0290\u8232 for he\'92s the mightiest one of all. But come,\u8232 let\'92s no longer talk this way, like little boys\u8232 standing in the middle of a battle.\u8232 Both of us have insults we could utter,\u8232 lots of them, so many that a cargo ship\u8232 with a hundred oars could not take on the load.\u8232 Men\'92s tongues are glib, with various languages\'97\u8232 words can go here and there in all directions,\u8232 and the sorts of words one speaks will be\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[250]\u8232 the sorts of words one has to listen to.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0300\u8232 But what\'92s the point? Why should the two of us\u8232 be squabbling here and fight by trading insults\u8232 back and forth, like two irritated women,\u8232 who, in some heart-wrenching raging spat,\u8232 go into the street to scream at one another\u8232 with facts and lies, each one gripped by anger.\u8232 I want to fight\'97your words won\'92t send me off,\u8232 not before we\'92ve fought it out with bronze,\u8232 man to man. So come. Let\'92s start this now\u8232 and test each other with our bronze-tipped spears.\'94\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0310\
